    {
      "role": "user",
      "content": "I'm trying to understand the fermentation process in my sourdough starter. specifically how the yeast and the bacteria work together. can you explain the relationship between the wild yeast and the lactobacilli and how temperature affects the balance between them?",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "In a sourdough starter, wild yeast (mainly Saccharomyces cerevisiae) and lactobacilli (specifically Lactobacillus sanfranciscensis) collaborate to ferment sugars. The yeast produces carbon dioxide, causing bubbles, while lactobacilli convert sugars into lactic acid, contributing to the sour taste. Ideally, the yeast and lactobacilli should maintain a delicate balance, with the yeast likely thriving at warmer temperatures (75-80°F) and lactobacilli preferring cooler temperatures (60-65°F). At temperatures above 85°F, lactobacilli can overgrow yeast, resulting in an overly sour starter, while temperatures below 60°F can slow yeast activity, favoring lactobacilli dominance.",
      "source": "target",
